{"version":3,"timestamp":"2026-02-10T18:28:31.196Z","sessions":{"0ed7979ff2777cd6":{"agent":"claude","model":"claude-opus-4-6","prompts":[{"id":20,"timestamp":"2026-02-10T01:06:01.339Z","content":"Base directory for this skill: /Users/marko/.claude/plugins/cache/superpowers-marketplace/superpowers/4.1.1/skills/executing-plans\n\n# Executing Plans\n\n## Overview\n\nLoad plan, review critically, execute tasks in batches, report for review between batches.\n\n**Core principle:** Batch execution with checkpoints for architect review.\n\n**Announce at start:** \"I'm using the executing-plans skill to implement this plan.\"\n\n## The Process\n\n### Step 1: Load and Review Plan\n1. Read plan file\n2. Review critically - identify any questions or concerns about the plan\n3. If concerns: Raise them with your human partner before starting\n4. If no concerns: Create TodoWrite and proceed\n\n### Step 2: Execute Batch\n**Default: First 3 tasks**\n\nFor each task:\n1. Mark as in_progress\n2. Follow each step exactly (plan has bite-sized steps)\n3. Run verifications as specified\n4. Mark as completed\n\n### Step 3: Report\nWhen batch complete:\n- Show what was implemented\n- Show verification output\n- Say: \"Ready for feedback.\"\n\n### Step 4: Continue\nBased on feedback:\n- Apply changes if needed\n- Execute next batch\n- Repeat until complete\n\n### Step 5: Complete Development\n\nAfter all tasks complete and verified:\n- Announce: \"I'm using the finishing-a-development-branch skill to complete this work.\"\n- **REQUIRED SUB-SKILL:** Use superpowers:finishing-a-development-branch\n- Follow that skill to verify tests, present options, execute choice\n\n## When to Stop and Ask for Help\n\n**STOP executing immediately when:**\n- Hit a blocker mid-batch (missing dependency, test fails, instruction unclear)\n- Plan has critical gaps preventing starting\n- You don't understand an instruction\n- Verification fails repeatedly\n\n**Ask for clarification rather than guessing.**\n\n## When to Revisit Earlier Steps\n\n**Return to Review (Step 1) when:**\n- Partner updates the plan based on your feedback\n- Fundamental approach needs rethinking\n\n**Don't force through blockers** - stop and ask.\n\n## Remember\n- Review plan critically first\n- Follow plan steps exactly\n- Don't skip verifications\n- Reference skills when plan says to\n- Between batches: just report and wait\n- Stop when blocked, don't guess\n","tools":{"read":7,"write":1,"edit":9},"duration":1369},{"id":22,"timestamp":"2026-02-10T01:28:50.791Z","content":"keep going","tools":{"read":10,"edit":19},"duration":1806},{"id":25,"timestamp":"2026-02-10T01:58:56.488Z","content":"Base directory for this skill: /Users/marko/.claude/plugins/cache/superpowers-marketplace/superpowers/4.1.1/skills/writing-plans\n\n# Writing Plans\n\n## Overview\n\nWrite comprehensive implementation plans assuming the engineer has zero context for our codebase and questionable taste. Document everything they need to know: which files to touch for each task, code, testing, docs they might need to check, how to test it. Give them the whole plan as bite-sized tasks. DRY. YAGNI. TDD. Frequent commits.\n\nAssume they are a skilled developer, but know almost nothing about our toolset or problem domain. Assume they don't know good test design very well.\n\n**Announce at start:** \"I'm using the writing-plans skill to create the implementation plan.\"\n\n**Context:** This should be run in a dedicated worktree (created by brainstorming skill).\n\n**Save plans to:** `docs/plans/YYYY-MM-DD-<feature-name>.md`\n\n## Bite-Sized Task Granularity\n\n**Each step is one action (2-5 minutes):**\n- \"Write the failing test\" - step\n- \"Run it to make sure it fails\" - step\n- \"Implement the minimal code to make the test pass\" - step\n- \"Run the tests and make sure they pass\" - step\n- \"Commit\" - step\n\n## Plan Document Header\n\n**Every plan MUST start with this header:**\n\n```markdown\n# [Feature Name] Implementation Plan\n\n> **For Claude:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:executing-plans to implement this plan task-by-task.\n\n**Goal:** [One sentence describing what this builds]\n\n**Architecture:** [2-3 sentences about approach]\n\n**Tech Stack:** [Key technologies/libraries]\n\n---\n```\n\n## Task Structure\n\n```markdown\n### Task N: [Component Name]\n\n**Files:**\n- Create: `exact/path/to/file.py`\n- Modify: `exact/path/to/existing.py:123-145`\n- Test: `tests/exact/path/to/test.py`\n\n**Step 1: Write the failing test**\n\n```python\ndef test_specific_behavior():\n    result = function(input)\n    assert result == expected\n```\n\n**Step 2: Run test to verify it fails**\n\nRun: `pytest tests/path/test.py::test_name -v`\nExpected: FAIL with \"function not defined\"\n\n**Step 3: Write minimal implementation**\n\n```python\ndef function(input):\n    return expected\n```\n\n**Step 4: Run test to verify it passes**\n\nRun: `pytest tests/path/test.py::test_name -v`\nExpected: PASS\n\n**Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add tests/path/test.py src/path/file.py\ngit commit -m \"feat: add specific feature\"\n```\n```\n\n## Remember\n- Exact file paths always\n- Complete code in plan (not \"add validation\")\n- Exact commands with expected output\n- Reference relevant skills with @ syntax\n- DRY, YAGNI, TDD, frequent commits\n\n## Execution Handoff\n\nAfter saving the plan, offer execution choice:\n\n**\"Plan complete and saved to `docs/plans/<filename>.md`. Two execution options:**\n\n**1. Subagent-Driven (this session)** - I dispatch fresh subagent per task, review between tasks, fast iteration\n\n**2. Parallel Session (separate)** - Open new session with executing-plans, batch execution with checkpoints\n\n**Which approach?\"**\n\n**If Subagent-Driven chosen:**\n- **REQUIRED SUB-SKILL:** Use superpowers:subagent-driven-development\n- Stay in this session\n- Fresh subagent per task + code review\n\n**If Parallel Session chosen:**\n- Guide them to open new session in worktree\n- **REQUIRED SUB-SKILL:** New session uses superpowers:executing-plans\n","tools":{"read":16},"duration":726},{"id":27,"timestamp":"2026-02-10T02:11:02.983Z","content":"This session is being continued from a previous conversation that ran out of context. The summary below covers the earlier portion of the conversation.\n\nAnalysis:\nLet me chronologically analyze the conversation:\n\n1. **Initial Request**: The user asked to implement a plan for an `AsyncICache` - an async, concurrency-safe dual of `src/fs/icache/cache.rs` that wraps each `IcbLike` in an `InFlight`/`Available` state machine using `scc::HashMap`.\n\n2. **Skill Invocations**: The assistant invoked `superpowers:using-superpowers`, then `superpowers:executing-plans` skill for implementing the plan.\n\n3. **Codebase Exploration**: Read existing files (`mod.rs`, `cache.rs`, `Cargo.toml`), checked `scc` API methods, verified the actual scc version (3.5.6 vs plan's 3.4.16), discovered `scan` doesn't exist (need `iter_sync` instead), verified `insert_sync` method signature.\n\n4. **Plan Review & Adjustments**: \n   - `table.insert(...)` → `table.insert_sync(...)` \n   - `scan(...)` → `iter_sync(...)` (closure returns `true` to continue)\n   - `update_async` closure receives `(&K, &mut V)` - plan's code already matches\n   - `remove_if_async` closure receives `&mut V` - plan's code already matches\n\n5. **Batch 1 Implementation (Tasks 1-3)**:\n   - **Task 1**: Created `async_cache.rs` with `IcbState` enum, `AsyncICache` struct, `new()`, `allocate_fh()`, `inode_count()`. Fixed `let_underscore_drop` warning by using `drop()`. Added module to `mod.rs`. Tests passed (2 tests).\n   - **Task 2**: Added `wait_for_available`, `mark_inflight`, `complete`, `contains`. Added `Arc` and `Notify` imports. Tests passed (5 tests).\n   - **Task 3**: Added `get_icb` and `get_icb_mut` with closure-based access and InFlight awaiting. Tests passed (9 tests).\n\n6. **User said \"keep going\"** for Batch 2.\n\n7. **Batch 2 Implementation (Tasks 4-6)**:\n   - **Task 4**: Added `insert_icb` and `entry_or_insert_icb` with InFlight awaiting via `entry_async` loop. Tests passed (13 tests).\n   - **Task 5**: Added `inc_rc` and `forget` with reference counting and eviction. Tests passed (17 tests).\n   - **Task 6**: Added `for_each` using `iter_sync`, updated `mod.rs` with `pub use async_cache::AsyncICache`. Tests passed (19 tests).\n\n8. **Clippy Fixes in Task 6**:\n   - Doc markdown: backtick `InFlight` in docs\n   - `expect_used`: replaced `.expect()` with `.unwrap_or_else(|| unreachable!())`\n   - `needless_continue`: removed redundant `continue`\n   - `allow_attributes`: changed `#[allow(...)]` to `#[expect(...)]`\n   - `unfulfilled_lint_expectations`: used `#[cfg_attr(not(test), expect(dead_code))]`\n   - Ran `cargo fmt` to auto-format\n\n9. **Finishing skill invoked**: All 19 tests pass, clippy clean, fmt clean.\n\n10. **User's CRITICAL FEEDBACK**: \"I severely dislike that [wait_for_available] is a spin-lock. What can we do to avoid the spin-lock?\"\n\n11. **Assistant's Analysis**: Identified two issues:\n    - The loop structure (aesthetic concern)\n    - A real race condition: if `complete()` fires between cloning `Arc<Notify>` and calling `.notified().await`, the notification is lost → permanent hang\n    \n    Presented two options:\n    - **Option A**: `get_async` + `enable()` pattern - keeps Notify, minimal change\n    - **Option B**: Replace `Notify` with `watch` channel - eliminates loop entirely\n\n12. **User chose Option B**: \"B is much better\" then interrupted to request a plan with additional requirements: Instead of manually managing `complete`, `AsyncICache`'s `I` trait needs a trait that's a \"promise that the IcbLike will eventually resolve\" - the cache should manage the lifecycle of the in-flight object altogether.\n\n13. **User invoked `/superpowers:write-plan`** with the argument about the resolver trait approach.\n\n14. **Writing-plans skill invoked**: The assistant began thoroughly exploring the codebase to understand all IcbLike implementations, usage patterns, and the full context needed for the plan.\n\n15. **Exploration Results**:\n    - 3 IcbLike implementations (local, mescloud, test)\n    - `mark_inflight`/`complete` only used in test code\n    - `AsyncICache` not used in production yet\n    - `bridge.rs` handles inode/filehandle translation between stacked FS layers\n    - Sync `ICache` is the active cache used by LocalFs and mescloud\n    - `Fs` trait in `trait.rs` is async with `#[async_trait]`\n    - Checked `watch::Receiver` API details\n\n16. **Plan Design Decisions** (assistant was in the middle of designing):\n    - `IcbResolver` trait with associated `Icb` type and `Error` type\n    - `AsyncICache<R: IcbResolver>` - single type parameter, ICB derived from `R::Icb`\n    - `IcbState::InFlight(watch::Receiver<()>)` replacing `Arc<Notify>`\n    - `get_or_resolve` method managing full InFlight lifecycle\n    - `mark_inflight`/`complete` removed from public API\n    - `wait_for_available` rewritten without loop (single wait + re-check)\n    - Stale InFlight detection via `rx.has_changed().is_err()`\n    - Using RPITIT (`impl Future<...> + Send`) instead of `async_trait` for the resolver\n\n17. **Plan Task Structure** being designed:\n    - Task 1: Add `IcbResolver` trait + make `AsyncICache` generic over resolver\n    - Task 2: Replace `Notify` with `watch` + rewrite `wait_for_available`\n    - Task 3: Add `get_or_resolve` method\n    - Task 4: Internalize InFlight management + cleanup\n\nThe assistant was in the process of writing the actual plan document to `docs/plans/2026-02-09-async-icache-resolver.md` when the summary was requested.\n\nKey files:\n- `src/fs/icache/async_cache.rs` - the main file created and modified\n- `src/fs/icache/mod.rs` - module wiring\n- `src/fs/icache/cache.rs` - sync reference implementation\n- `src/fs/trait.rs` - Inode, FileHandle types, Fs trait\n- `src/fs/local.rs` - LocalFs IcbLike implementation\n- `src/fs/mescloud/icache.rs` - Mescloud IcbLike implementation\n- `src/fs/icache/bridge.rs` - inode/filehandle bridge\n\nCurrent state of `async_cache.rs`: fully implemented with 19 passing tests, clippy clean, fmt clean. But needs the refactor described in the plan being written.\n\nCurrent state of `mod.rs`:\n```rust\n#[cfg_attr(not(test), expect(dead_code))]\npub mod async_cache;\npub mod bridge;\nmod cache;\nmod inode_factory;\n\n#[expect(unused_imports)]\npub use async_cache::AsyncICache;\npub use cache::ICache;\npub use inode_factory::InodeFactory;\n\npub trait IcbLike {\n    fn new_root(path: std::path::PathBuf) -> Self;\n    fn rc(&self) -> u64;\n    fn rc_mut(&mut self) -> &mut u64;\n}\n```\n\nSummary:\n1. Primary Request and Intent:\n   The user initially requested implementation of an `AsyncICache` — an async, concurrency-safe dual of the sync `ICache` in `src/fs/icache/cache.rs`. This was implemented across 6 tasks with 19 passing tests. The user then raised a critical concern about the `wait_for_available` method being a spin-lock, and after discussing two fix options, chose **Option B** (replace `Notify` with `watch` channels). The user then expanded the scope significantly: instead of just fixing the spin-lock, they want a full refactor where `AsyncICache` gains an `IcbResolver` trait — a \"promise that the IcbLike will eventually resolve, exactly to fetch the underlying data\" — so the cache manages the entire InFlight lifecycle internally, removing the need for callers to manually call `mark_inflight`/`complete`. The user explicitly invoked `/superpowers:write-plan` to create an implementation plan for this refactor.\n\n2. Key Technical Concepts:\n   - `scc::HashMap` (v3.5.6) — lock-free concurrent hashmap with closure-based access (`read_async`, `update_async`, `upsert_async`, `entry_async`, `remove_if_async`, `iter_sync`)\n   - `tokio::sync::watch` — channel with `Sender`/`Receiver` where `Receiver::changed().await` returns `Err(RecvError)`