ing the actual plan document** to `docs/plans/2026-02-09-async-icache-resolver.md` when the summary was requested.\n   \n   The planned design decisions were finalized:\n   ```rust\n   // New resolver trait\n   pub trait IcbResolver: Send + Sync {\n       type Icb: IcbLike + Send + Sync;\n       type Error: Send;\n       fn resolve(&self, ino: Inode) -> impl Future<Output = Result<Self::Icb, Self::Error>> + Send;\n   }\n   \n   // Updated IcbState\n   pub enum IcbState<I> {\n       InFlight(watch::Receiver<()>),\n       Available(I),\n   }\n   \n   // Updated AsyncICache — single type param, ICB derived from resolver\n   pub struct AsyncICache<R: IcbResolver> {\n       resolver: R,\n       inode_table: ConcurrentHashMap<Inode, IcbState<R::Icb>>,\n       next_fh: AtomicU64,\n   }\n   ```\n\n9. Optional Next Step:\n   Write the plan document to `docs/plans/2026-02-09-async-icache-resolver.md` with the full TDD task breakdown, exact code snippets, test code, and verification commands — then offer the execution choice per the writing-plans skill (\"Plan complete and saved. Two execution options: 1. Subagent-Driven, 2. Parallel Session. Which approach?\").\n   \n   Direct quote from user's most recent request: *\"I think this whole file needs slight reworking though. As a matter of fact, instead of manually managing complete, AsyncICache's I trait needs to have some sort of trait which is a promise that the IcbLike will eventually resolve, exactly to fetch the underlying data. Then, it can manage the lifecycle of the in-flight object altogether.\"*\n   \n   The assistant was actively working on writing this plan using the `writing-plans` skill format when interrupted.\n\nIf you need specific details from before compaction (like exact code snippets, error messages, or content you generated), read the full transcript at: /Users/marko/.claude/projects/-Users-marko-Desktop-gitfs-git-fs/a805fb74-88a7-4806-b478-9412d2b1f9b8.jsonl\nPlease continue the conversation from where we